:::summary
William Wilberforce (1759–1833) was the British Member of Parliament and Evangelical Christian whose twenty-six-year parliamentary campaign to abolish the slave trade in the British Empire stands as one of the greatest moral achievements in the history of democratic government — proof that a single person of faith, conviction, and tireless persistence can change the world.
:::

